# Public Code Documentation Rule

All source code must include public documentation that explains intent and behavior.

## Required documentation for changed/new code

- Every public source file must include a short top-level doc comment describing:
  - the file's intent,
  - the main responsibilities,
  - important side effects (if any).
- Every public function/method must include a doc comment that explains:
  - purpose and behavior,
  - all parameters (name, meaning, and expected shape/range),
  - return value,
  - side effects and error behavior when relevant.
- For classes/components/modules, document the integration, configuration, and communication APIs.

## Parameter documentation policy

- Document all parameters explicitly; do not skip optional/defaulted parameters.
- For callbacks, document callback signature and when it is invoked.
- For structured objects, document expected keys and constraints.

## Delivery checks before finalizing changes

- New/updated source files include top-level intent comments.
- New/updated public functions and methods include parameter docs.
- Documentation reflects current behavior after refactors.
